<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Morphology. D VI + I,8–11; A I,7–9; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[629,723,649,675]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">P 16–18</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, P. J." box="[739,879,649,675]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="305 - 334" refId="ref61216" refString="Miller, P. J. (1971) A revision of the Mediterranean gobiid genus Chromogobius (Teleostei Perciformes). Journal of Zoology, London, 164, 305 - 334. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1971. tb 01321. x" type="journal article" year="1971">Miller 1971</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Small goby with elongate body. Head clearly depressed (distinctly dorsoventrally flattened)</emphasis>
, head and predorsal profile horizontal (
<figureCitation box="[1135,1231,685,711]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
). Snout prominent and mouth opening upwards (
<figureCitation box="[481,577,721,747]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
). Caudal peduncle deep, almost as high as body. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin may be slightly higher in appearance, with more or less rounded shape and no elongate spines. Caudal fin rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Body fawn, brown or blackish with a broad pale predorsal bar extending ventrally on pectoral-fin base</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[362,444,865,891]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
), in some specimens indistinct. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[791,1309,865,891]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">No pale saddle at origin of the first dorsal fin</emphasis>
, prominent to poorly visible white saddle at origin of the second dorsal fin (
<figureCitation box="[857,952,901,927]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24a</figureCitation>
), while another short saddle may be present below posterior part of that fin (
<figureCitation box="[504,602,937,964]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24b</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[620,1436,937,963]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Tip of lower jaw, top of snout and interorbital space grayish or white.</emphasis>
Head usually with reticulate pattern, including cheeks (
<figureCitation box="[773,869,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1399,1423]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetId="figure-19@26.[151,1436,181,1375]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 24. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photos by A) S. Engin, Aegean Sea, Turkey and B) M. Colombo, Area Marina Protetta Capo Caccia-Isola Piana, Alghero, Sardinia, Italy." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24a</figureCitation>
), or cheeks densely dotted (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1278,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-18@25.[151,1436,181,1677]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 23. Head clearly depressed (dorsoventrally flattened). A) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, photo by M. Colombo. B) Chromogobius zebratus, photo by M. Kovačić, photographed in a tank." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J." pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="101 - 110" refId="ref52673" refString="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J. (2013) The importance of underwater photography in detecting cryptobenthic species: new in situ records of some gobies (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from Italian Seas with ecological notes. Acta Adriatica, 54 (1), 101 - 110." type="journal article" year="2013">Colombo &amp; Langeneck 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P." box="[353,667,1009,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref52296" refString="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P. (2017) Marine fishes of the Crimean Peninsula, second edition. Business-Inform, Simpheropol, 376 pp." type="book" year="2017">Boltachev &amp; Karpova 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Trkov, D. &amp; Mavric, B. &amp; Orlando-Bonaca, M. &amp; Lipej, L." box="[680,880,1009,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="59 - 72" refId="ref65518" refString="Trkov, D., Mavric, B., Orlando-Bonaca, M. &amp; Lipej, L. (2019) Marine cryptobenthic fish fauna of Slovenia (Northern Adriatic Sea). Annales, Series Historia Naturalis, 29 (1), 59 - 72. https: // doi. org / 10.19233 / ASHN. 2019.07" type="journal article" year="2019">
Trkov 
<emphasis box="[755,805,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Scales present, small, at best visible on body as pattern of pale dots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" box="[199,658,1081,1108]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kolombatovic" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[383,651,1081,1107]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Chromogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebratus">
<emphasis box="[383,651,1081,1107]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Chromogobius zebratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, 
<quantity box="[531,603,1117,1144]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="m" value="1.0" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.0">0–2 m</quantity>
depth on rocky shores, in clefts, below stones, hidden in biocover, in the Black Sea also in brackish waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Kovacic, M." box="[541,702,1153,1179]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="423 - 435" refId="ref57644" refString="Kovacic, M. (1997) Cryptobenthic gobies and clingfishes in the Kvarner area, Adriatic Sea. Natura Croatica, 6 (4), 423 - 435." type="journal article" year="1997">Kovačić 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Patzner, R. A." box="[714,865,1153,1180]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref62855" refString="Patzner, R. A. (2021) Gobiidae. Available from: http: // www. patzner. sbg. ac. at / Gobiidae / GobiidaeSpecies. htm (accessed 1 October 2021)" type="url" year="2021">Patzner 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,613,1288]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean and Black Sea (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ahnelt, H." box="[1004,1150,1189,1215]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="27 - 41" refId="ref50152" refString="Ahnelt, H. (1990) Chromogobius quadrivittatus, Chromogobius zebratus und Zebrus zebrus (Pisces: Gobiidae: Erstnachweis fur Korsika (Frankreich) und Sardinien (Italien). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 91, 27 - 41." type="journal article" year="1990">Ahnelt 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J." pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="101 - 110" refId="ref52673" refString="Colombo, M. &amp; Langeneck, J. (2013) The importance of underwater photography in detecting cryptobenthic species: new in situ records of some gobies (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from Italian Seas with ecological notes. Acta Adriatica, 54 (1), 101 - 110." type="journal article" year="2013">Colombo &amp; Langeneck 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P." box="[222,538,1225,1252]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref52296" refString="Boltachev, A. R. &amp; Karpova, E. P. (2017) Marine fishes of the Crimean Peninsula, second edition. Business-Inform, Simpheropol, 376 pp." type="book" year="2017">Boltachev &amp; Karpova 2017</bibRefCitation>
). In the Mediterranean Sea, there are records from northwestern Mediterranean, Adriatic Sea, 
<collectingRegion box="[303,389,1262,1288]" country="Greece" name="Voreio Aigaio" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Aegean</collectingRegion>
Sea and Levant (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
